2. Then apply `image g` to $f(u)$: This gives $g(f(u)) \in U$.

We know from the hypothesis $g \circ f = \text{id}$ that $g(f(u)) = u$ for all $u \in U$. 

So, $(\text{image } g \circ \text{image } f)(u) = g(f(u)) = u = \text{id}(u)$.

This shows that $\text{image } g \circ \text{image } f = \text{id}$.

