Therefore, we've shown that `(image g) ∘ (image f) u = u` for all `u ∈ U`, which proves that `(image g) ∘ (image f) = id`.

The complete proof is remarkably concise because the definitions align perfectly with the hypothesis `g ∘ f = id`. The key insight is that `image g` applied to the singleton set `{f u}` (which is what `image f u` becomes) results in the singleton set `{u}` because `g (f u) = u`.
